content.description:
Balancy and slabby moves tick-tack up a faint crack, eventually leading to a challenging sequence  fifteen feet off the deck and your first opportunity for substantial gear.  As the route progresses, another short series of fingery moves gets to easier climbing and the sloping top-out.  

 Though short, this route is sustained and somewhat cryptic.  Bring nerves of steel--you'll need 'em!
content.protection: Small gear up to a .5 Camalot.  Chain anchor on the top.
content.location: 50 yards off the road on the right side of the Tumbledown Mountain.  This small crag is called the Forehead, and has the easiest access of all the mini-craglets scattering the hillside.

content.description: Short route but solid moves most of the way.
content.protection: Following the crack, which takes some small/ cams you climb the crack to the top where there is a double chain anchor (shared anchor with Shylocks).
content.location: Start to the right of the white birch.   This route is the left leaning crack to the right of Shylocks.

content.description: Small but nice climbs on this 45-50 ft crag that are often top-roped.
